data.content:
Great question — this is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, `AddScoped` = one instance **per HTTP request**. Each request automatically creates and disposes a scope.

**In MAUI, there are no request-based scopes.** The app has a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` lives for the entire app lifetime, accumulating tracked entities and stale data.

### Fixes

**Option 1 — Use `AddTransient`:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
A new context per injection. Simple, but you lose shared-context-per-unit-of-work.

**Option 2 — Use `IDbContextFactory` (recommended):**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(opts =>
    opts.UseSqlite("..."));
```
Then inject and create short-lived contexts explicitly:
```csharp
public class MyViewModel
{
    private readonly IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> _factory;

    public MyViewModel(IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> factory)
        => _factory = factory;

    public async Task LoadData()
    {
        using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();
        Items = await db.Items.ToListAsync();
    }
}
```

**Option 3 — Manual scopes via `IServiceScopeFactory`:**
```csharp
using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();
var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
```

Option 2 (`AddDbContextFactory`) is the most idiomatic — it makes the context lifetime explicit and avoids the tracking/memory issues of a long-lived `DbContext`.
